<div id="review_256271878" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/256271878" />
    <a title="Christina Rau" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7310711-christina-rau"><img alt="Christina Rau" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1486871549p2/7310711.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/256271878?book_show_action=true">Jan 04, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christina Rau" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christina Rau" href="/user/show/7310711-christina-rau">Christina Rau</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7310711-christina-rau?shelf=poetry">poetry</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer256271878" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1619998680497186521">Yusef Komunyakaa has two types of poetry. One type is talky, conversational, and story-like. The other is lyrical, imagery-filled, and layered. I like the latter more. He shows off his unique sense of the world through those. His poems about military life also offer a view into a world many do not know; however, I&apos;m not a fan of that kind of poetry. I do appreciate activist poetry, but the poems about army life are not enticing for me. Still, he weaves them in a seemingly effortless manner, whic</span>
  <span id="freeText1619998680497186521" style="display:none">Yusef Komunyakaa has two types of poetry. One type is talky, conversational, and story-like. The other is lyrical, imagery-filled, and layered. I like the latter more. He shows off his unique sense of the world through those. His poems about military life also offer a view into a world many do not know; however, I'm not a fan of that kind of poetry. I do appreciate activist poetry, but the poems about army life are not enticing for me. Still, he weaves them in a seemingly effortless manner, which only means that he most likely spends hours and hours finding the right memory and the right word to produce it. Neon Vernacular is filled with new and old poems in an interesting order that swings between the two extremes of his patterns. The words and lines remain fresh through to the end. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1619998680497186521" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


