    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2354617597" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2354617597" />
    <a title="Liam" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9586694-liam"><img alt="Liam" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1337257924p2/9586694.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2354617597?book_show_action=true">Apr 08, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Liam" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Liam" href="/user/show/9586694-liam">Liam</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2354617597" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16964690278277012346">As a younger student, and uncontrollably ablaze with an itch for poetry, I stumbled upon a journalist, whose language seemed more like a history of a war, than prose. Vietnam has enamored the darkest in each of us after that era and no other writer, photographer, historian or professor has managed to construct the most ominous of testimony, as Yusef Komunyakaa. His collections of radical observation, including Neon Vernacular, take what has happened to him as a journalist and explored these ugly</span>
  <span id="freeText16964690278277012346" style="display:none">As a younger student, and uncontrollably ablaze with an itch for poetry, I stumbled upon a journalist, whose language seemed more like a history of a war, than prose. Vietnam has enamored the darkest in each of us after that era and no other writer, photographer, historian or professor has managed to construct the most ominous of testimony, as Yusef Komunyakaa. His collections of radical observation, including Neon Vernacular, take what has happened to him as a journalist and explored these ugly subjects to the credit of his own healing scars, equal to our own minimum standard of just being human. Neon Vernacular won the Pulitzer Prize for Literature in 1994 and is composed of several collections. <br />	His language and imagery are a simply searing sauna of Vietnamese, American and every town in-between. He reminds the reader of a harrowing history with Salt, a poem that remembers an old girlfriend, however not her name. The speaker unwinds his suspicion that the now woman is fearful of him, rather his color, and no longer remembers him for his spirit they shared, even as a child’s romance. “I remember/ She was seven &amp; I was five/ When she ran up to me like a cat/ With a gypsy moth in its mouth/ &amp; we played doctor &amp; house/ Under the low branches of a raintree/ Encircled with red rhododendrons” (Komunyakaa 6). His poem’s title entrenches a certain vision of cleansed whiteness throughout and ends with “it’s hard now not to walk over/ &amp; mention how her grandmother/ Killed her idiot son/ &amp; salted him down/ In a wooden barrel” (Komunyakaa 7). The angles of exploration is cause for the reader to take great pause, on a social scale, as well as on personal, to examine their own relationship with the history of their own family.<br />	Another device used in this award-winning collection, is the idea of formatting. Komunyakaa uses various forms of poetry and syntax, not often seen in such a melodic context. Komunyakaa uses two columns to write the poem Changes; or, Reveries at a Window Overlooking a Country Road, with Two Women Talking Blues in the Kitchen. The reader can hear the rhythms of an ole dusty guitar as he writes the narrative, “Rhythm/ like cells multiplying… language &amp;/ notes made flesh. Accents &amp; stresses/ almost sexual” (Komunyakaa 8). The lyrics of his poetry causes the foot to stomp and head to bob and sway, like few other writers of the time. He references “Mingus” and “Django”, all together in one symphonic swaying of language along the page.<br />	A notable trait of Komunyakaa that cannot be easily understated is his attention to detail. Through short-lines and specifically small-framed stanzas that cast immeasurable light on the very minute detail of its subjects. Towards the latter of his collection lies another gem that best displays his pure technique. His poem Facing It, reached deep into his memories concerning the Vietnam war and the way it leaves scars those who were there, or indirectly, have lost someone close to them there. He writes, “My black face fades,/ hiding inside the black granite,/ I said I wouldn’t,/ dammit: No tears” (Komunyakaa 159) as a preface to his own statements, mostly sharp memories and mournful losses of his own friends in war. He admits that he “goes down the 58,022 names,/ half-expecting to find/ my own letters like smoke” (Komunyakaa 159). His heart is broken from his own experience there and he sees his memories in the stone, in the names and in those who have come to see the Memorial. His imagery plays with the minds of the reader, just the stone plays optical illusions on him, while he investigates the glassy stone. He writes again “A white vet’s image floats/ closer to me, then his pale eyes/ look through mine. I’m a window./ He’s lost his right arm/ inside the stone.” (Komunyakaa 159). <br />	Yusef Komunyakaa has served as the professor in the Council of Humanities and Creative Writing at Princeton University and is the author of several other, award-winning titles, some of which are included in this collection. As a master of double consciousness, he interweaves his memory with history, all through an African-American male identity. His work allows any reader to take a few steps or walk entire countries, in his well-established jungle boots, and in upon arrival, land on redefined landscape, of striking color, unique juxtaposition and honest introspection.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16964690278277012346" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


