<div id="review_2718246079" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2718246079" />
    <a title="boocia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/75684923-boocia"><img alt="boocia" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2718246079?book_show_action=true">Jul 21, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="boocia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="boocia" href="/user/show/75684923-boocia">boocia</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/75684923-boocia?shelf=2019-poetry">2019-poetry</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/75684923-boocia?shelf=2019">2019</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2718246079" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3245308484876993926">this was a rough slog by the end but there were a few gems also<br/><br/>by virtue of being a sampling of poems from across his collections there wasn&apos;t quite as much cohesion or focus, of course, across all of the poems. the lack of focus made the whole thing sort of a blur. <br/><br/>i think the blues-y jazz-y imagist-y poems flowed really well, felt really good in the mouth as it were, but weren&apos;t quite as semantically pointed as i would like? maybe i&apos;m just not into impressionistic-forward poems right now. <br/><br/>ther</span>
  <span id="freeText3245308484876993926" style="display:none">this was a rough slog by the end but there were a few gems also<br /><br />by virtue of being a sampling of poems from across his collections there wasn't quite as much cohesion or focus, of course, across all of the poems. the lack of focus made the whole thing sort of a blur. <br /><br />i think the blues-y jazz-y imagist-y poems flowed really well, felt really good in the mouth as it were, but weren't quite as semantically pointed as i would like? maybe i'm just not into impressionistic-forward poems right now. <br /><br />there are a lot of poems about regret/yearning which is nice and what i was hoping for, because i am reading eros the bittersweet which is also about yearning. lots of triangulations of what is, and what could/should have been, and the separation between those, which is primarily the vietnam war. so, pleasing to think about even though i think the inundation sort of wore me out.<br /><br />he also has a really weird obsession with women/sex that i have a hard time wrapping my head around. i think it has this sort of hemingway-esque smack to it, of using sex to smother war, but then women sort of become tools of comfort and not really people.<br /><br />it'd probably be better to just read the original collections instead of this compilation<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3245308484876993926" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


