<div id="review_613417137" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/613417137" />
    <a title="Mike" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1398087-mike"><img alt="Mike" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1532541897p2/1398087.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/613417137?book_show_action=true">Jan 16, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mike" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mike" href="/user/show/1398087-mike">Mike</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1398087-mike?shelf=poetry-books">poetry-books</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer613417137" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11408494156481199793">&quot;Looking A Mad Dog Dead in the Eyes,&quot; &quot;Thanks,&quot; and &quot;Facing It&quot; are as haunting as when I first encountered them almost twenty years ago (Nov. 2001 is when Yusef signed my copy). This is a staggering account of the traumas of both Blackness and Vietnam, a rhapsodic exegesis not just of jazz but the demons of the jazz greats, and a chronicling - in reverse - of Komunyakaa&apos;s ascent into a wholly distinct genius of rhythm &amp; voice that abounds in his later <i>Thieves of Paradise.</i><br/><br/>Again, just a great col</span>
  <span id="freeText11408494156481199793" style="display:none">"Looking A Mad Dog Dead in the Eyes," "Thanks," and "Facing It" are as haunting as when I first encountered them almost twenty years ago (Nov. 2001 is when Yusef signed my copy). This is a staggering account of the traumas of both Blackness and Vietnam, a rhapsodic exegesis not just of jazz but the demons of the jazz greats, and a chronicling - in reverse - of Komunyakaa's ascent into a wholly distinct genius of rhythm &amp; voice that abounds in his later <i>Thieves of Paradise.</i><br /><br />Again, just a great collection of great work by a distinct, no-punches-pulled, Black Original Voice. Worth checking out for anyone remotely interested in poetry. These poems conjured my image of Mr. Komunyakaa reading these - so vividly, so wondrously - just two months after September 11th in my high school library. A fierce document indeed.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11408494156481199793" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

